aa(lp22
VThis is a picture of the George Mark Children's House,
p23
aVthe first pediatric palliative respite care center
p24
aVto open in the United States.
p25
aVI founded it in 2004,
p26
aVafter years of working as a psychologist
p27
aVon pediatric intensive care units,
p28
aVfrustrated with the undignified deaths that so many children experienced
p29
aVand their families had to endure.
p30
aVAs I sat with families whose children were at the end of their lives,
p31
aVI was acutely aware of our surroundings.
p32
aVWhile the elevated train rumbled overhead on its track,
p33
aVquite literally the room reverberated with each passing train car.
p34
aVThe lights on the ward were fluorescent and too bright.
p35
aVMonitors beeped, as did the elevator,
p36
aVnoisily announcing its arrival.
p37
aVThese families were experiencing
p38
aVsome of the most excruciating moments of their lives,
p39
aVand I so wanted them to have a more peaceful place
p40
aVin which to say a last goodbye to their young daughters and sons.
p41
aVSurely, I thought,
p42
aVthere must be a better spot than a hospital intensive care unit
p43
aVfor children at the end of their lives.
p44
aa(lp45
VOur children's house
p46
aVis calm and nurturing.
p47
aVIt's a place where families can stay together
p48
aVto enjoy quality time with their children,
p49
aVmany of whom are there for respite stays,
p50
aVsome with repeated visits over a span of many years.
p51
aVWe call those kids our frequent flyers.
p52
aVRather than the bright, noisy quarters of the hospital,
p53
aVtheir rooms are calm and comfortable,
p54
aVwith actual living spaces for the families,
p55
aVa sanctuary of gardens
p56
aVand a wonderful outdoor playground
p57
aVwith special structures for children with physical limitations.
