aa(lp59
VThis sweet baby Lars
p60
aVcame to us directly from a hospital intensive care unit.
p61
aVImagine hearing the heartbreaking news
p62
aVthat none of us would ever want to hear.
p63
aVHis parents had been told that Lars had a brain anomaly
p64
aVthat would keep him from ever swallowing,
p65
aVwalking, talking
p66
aVor developing mentally.
p67
aVRecognizing what little chance he had for survival,
p68
aVhis parents chose to focus on the quality of time
p69
aVthat they could spend together.
p70
aVThey moved into one of our family apartments
p71
aVand treasured each day that they had,
p72
aVwhich were far too few.
p73
aVLars's life was brief, to be sure,
p74
aVmere weeks,
p75
aVbut it was calm and comfortable.
p76
aVHe went on hikes with his parents.
p77
aVThe time that he spent in the pool with our aquatic therapist
p78
aVlessened the seizures he was experiencing
p79
aVand helped him to sleep at night.
p80
aVHis family had a peaceful place
p81
aVin which to both celebrate his life
p82
aVand mourn his death.
p83
aa(lp84
VIt has been five years since Lars was with us,
p85
aVand in that time,
p86
aVhis family has welcomed
p87
aVa daughter and another son.
p88
aVThey are such a powerful testament
p89
aVto the positive outcome that specialized children's hospice care can create.
p90
aVTheir baby's physical discomfort was well managed,
p91
aVgiving all of them the gift of time to be together in a beautiful place.
