aa(lp93
VI'm going to talk to you now
p94
aVabout the elephant
p95
aVrather than the camel in the room.
p96
aVVery few people want to talk about death,
p97
aVand even fewer about children's death.
p98
aVLoss of a child,
p99
aVespecially for those of us who have our own children,
p100
aVis frightening,
p101
aVmore than frightening,
p102
aVparalyzing,
p103
aVdebilitating,
p104
aVimpossible.
p105
aVBut what I've learned is this:
p106
aVchildren don't stop dying
p107
aVjust because we the adults
p108
aVcan't comprehend the injustice of losing them.
p109
aVAnd what's more,
p110
aVif we can be brave enough
p111
aVto face the possibility of death,
p112
aVeven among the most innocent,
p113
aVwe gain an unparalleled kind of wisdom.
p114
aa(lp115
VTake Crystal, for example.
p116
aVShe was one of the first children to come for care
p117
aVafter we opened our doors.
p118
aVShe was nine when she arrived,
p119
aVand her neurologist expected that she might live another two weeks.
p120
aVShe had an inoperable brain tumor,
p121
aVand her decline had really accelerated
p122
aVin the week before she came to us.
p123
aVAfter settling into her room,
p124
aVdressed entirely in pink and lavender,
p125
aVsurrounded by the Hello Kitty accessories that she loved,
p126
aVshe spent the next several days
p127
aVwinning over the hearts of every staff member.
p128
aVBit by bit, her condition stabilized,
p129
aVand then to our astonishment,
p130
aVshe actually improved.
p131
aVThere were a variety of factors
p132
aVthat contributed to Crystal's improvement
p133
aVwhich we later came to call the "George Mark bump,"
p134
aVa lovely, not uncommon phenomenon
p135
aVwhere children outlive the prognoses of their illnesses
p136
aVif they're outside of the hospital.
p137
aVThe calmer atmosphere of her surroundings,
p138
aVtasty meals that were fixed often to accommodate her requests,
p139
aVthe resident pets,
p140
aVthe therapy dog and rabbit spent lots of cozy time with Crystal.
p141
aa(lp142
VAfter she had been with us for about a week,
p143
aVshe called her grandmother,
p144
aVand she said,
p145
aV"Gee, I'm staying in a great big house,
p146
aVand there's room for you to come, too.
p147
aVAnd guess what?
p148
aVYou don't have to bring any quarters
p149
aVbecause the washer and dryer are free."
p150
aa(lp151
V(Laughter)
p152
aa(lp153
VCrystal's grandmother soon arrived from out of town,
p154
aVand they spent the remaining four months of Crystal's life
p155
aVenjoying very special days together.
p156
aVSome days were special because Crystal was outside in her wheelchair
p157
aVsitting by the fountain.
p158
aVFor a little girl who had spent most of the year earlier in a hospital bed,
p159
aVbeing outside counting hummingbirds
p160
aVmade for an amazing time with her grandma,
p161
aVand lots of laughter.
p162
aVOther days were special because of the activities
p163
aVthat our child life specialist created for her.
p164
aVCrystal strung beads and made jewelry for everybody in the house.
p165
aVShe painted a pumpkin to help decorate for Halloween.
p166
aVShe spent many excited days planning her tenth birthday,
p167
aVwhich of course none of us thought she would ever see.
p168
aVAll of us wore pink boas for the occasion,
p169
aVand Crystal, as you can see,
p170
aVqueen for a day,
p171
aVwore a sparkly tiara.
p172
aa(lp173
VOne hot morning, I arrived at work
p174
aVand Crystal and her partner in crime, Charlie, greeted me.
p175
aVWith some help, they had set up a lemonade and cookie stand
p176
aVoutside the front door,
p177
aVa very strategic location.
p178
aVI asked Crystal the price of the cookie that I had selected,
p179
aVand she said, "Three dollars."
p180
aa(lp181
V(Laughter)
p182
aa(lp183
VI said that seemed a bit high for one cookie.
p184
aa(lp185
V(Laughter)
p186
aa(lp187
VIt was small.
p188
aV"I know," she acknowledged with a grin,
p189
aV"but I'm worth it."
p190
aa(lp191
VAnd therein lie the words of wisdom
p192
aVof a young girl whose brief life forever impacted mine.
p193
aVCrystal was worth it,
p194
aVand shouldn't every child whose life is shortened by a horrific illness
p195
aVbe worth it?
p196
aVTogether, all of us today
p197
aVcan offer that same specialized care that Crystal received
p198
aVby recognizing that children's respite and hospice care
p199
aVis a critical component missing from our healthcare landscape.
p200
aVIt's also interesting to note
p201
aVthat we are able to provide this care
p202
aVat about one third of the cost of a hospital intensive care unit,
p203
aVand our families don't see a bill.
p204
aVWe are ever grateful to the supporters
p205
aVwho believe in this important work that we're doing.
p206
aa(lp207
VThe truth is that my colleagues and I
p208
aVand the parents and other family members
p209
aVwho get to experience this special wisdom
p210
aVare in a unique position.
p211
aVThere are only two freestanding pediatric hospices in the United States,
p212
aValthough I'm happy to report that based on our model,
p213
aVthere are 18 others under various stages of development.
p214
aa(lp215
V(Applause)
p216
aa(lp217
VStill, most of the children who die in the United States every year
p218
aVdie in hospital rooms,
p219
aVsurrounded by beeping machines
p220
aVand anxious, exhausted adults
p221
aVwho have no other option
p222
aVbut to say goodbye under those harsh, institutional lights
p223
aVand among virtual strangers.
p224
aVFor comparison's sake,
p225
aVthe United Kingdom,
p226
aVwhich is a country with about one fifth the population of the United States,
p227
aVand about half the size of the state of California,
p228
aVhas 54 hospice and respite centers.
p229
aVWhy is that?
p230
aVI've asked myself that question obviously many times.
p231
aVMy best guess is that Americans, with our positive can-do attitude
p232
aVhold the expectation that our medical care system will fix it,
p233
aVeven though it may be a childhood illness for which there is no cure.
p234
aVWe go to extraordinary measures to keep children alive
p235
aVwhen in fact the greatest kindness that we might give them
p236
aVwould be a peaceful, pain-free
p237
aVend of life.
p238
aVThe transition from cure to care
p239
aVremains a challenging one for many hospital physicians
p240
aVwhose training has really been about saving lives,
p241
aVnot about gently guiding the patient to the end of life.
p242
aVThe dad of a sweet baby for whom we cared at the end of her life
p243
aVcertainly captured this dichotomy
p244
aVwhen he reflected
p245
aVthat there are a lot of people to help you bring an infant into the world
p246
aVbut very few to help you usher a baby out.
p247
aa(lp248
VSo what is the magic ingredient at George Mark?
p249
aVThe complex medical diagnoses that bring our young patients to us
p250
aVmean that their lives have often been restricted,
p251
aVsome to a hospital bed for long periods of time,
p252
aVothers to wheelchairs,
p253
aVstill others to intensive courses of chemotherapy or rehab.
p254
aVWe make a practice of ignoring those limitations.
p255
aVOur default answer is "yes"
p256
aVand our default question is, "Why not?"
p257
aVThat's why we took a young boy
p258
aVwho wasn't going to live for another baseball season
p259
aVto Game 5 of the World Series.
p260
aVThat's why we have a talent show put on by the staff and kids
p261
aVfor family and friends.
p262
aVWho wouldn't be enchanted by a young boy playing a piano piece with his feet,
p263
aVbecause his arms are atrophied?
p264
aVThat's why we have a prom every year.
p265
aVIt's pretty magical.
p266
aVWe started the prom
p267
aVafter hearing a dad lament
p268
aVthat he would never pin a boutonniere on his son's tuxedo lapel.
p269
aVThe weeks before the dance,
p270
aVthe house is in a flurry,
p271
aVand I don't know who's more excited, the staff or the kids.
p272
aa(lp273
V(Laughter)
p274
aa(lp275
VThe night of the event
p276
aVinvolves rides in vintage cars,
p277
aVa walk on a red carpet
p278
aVinto the great room,
p279
aVa terrific DJ
p280
aVand a photographer at the ready
p281
aVto capture pictures of these attendees
p282
aVand their families.
p283
aVAt the end of the evening this year,
p284
aVone of our young, delightful teenaged girls,
p285
aVCaitlin, said to her mom,
p286
aV"That was the best night of my whole life."
p287
aVAnd that's just the point,
p288
aVto capture the best days and nights,
p289
aVto abolish limitations,
p290
aVto have your default answer be "yes"
p291
aVand your default question be, "Why not?"
p292
aa(lp293
VUltimately life is too short,
p294
aVwhether we live to be 85 years or just eight.
p295
aVTrust me.
p296
aVBetter yet, trust Sam.
p297
aVIt's not by pretending that death doesn't exist
p298
aVthat we keep the people,
p299
aVespecially the little people that we love,
p300
aVsafe.
p301
aVIn the end,
p302
aVwe can't control how long any of us lives.
p303
aVWhat we can control
p304
aVis how we spend our days,
p305
aVthe spaces we create,
p306
aVthe meaning and joy that we make.
p307
aVWe cannot change the outcome,
p308
aVbut we can change the journey.
p309
aVIsn't it time
p310
aVto recognize that children deserve
p311
aVnothing less than our most uncompromising bravery
p312
aVand our wildest imagination.
